Glad you found us.

I live in Indiana and am in my early 60s.  I _always_ make the 
distinction between Why and Way and always have.  That is my natural 
pronunciation, but I know that I am in the minority now in the U.S.  I 
have five brothers and I am the eldest.  The brother born after me also 
pronounces Why.  The other three do not, and we were all raised in the 
same family.  It seems very curious to me for this difference in speech 
to exist over such a short period of time.

I suspect that you think of the &quot;h&quot; in the digraph &quot;wh&quot; as a silent 
letter.  I recently heard of an elementary teacher, who, no doubt, 
shared your lack of Why in her idiolect, and she taught her students 
that the &quot;h&quot; was silent.  I was stunned because it was clear that she 
viewed her idiolect as &quot;normal&quot; and did not realize that a significant 
percentage of the U.S. population still pronounces the &quot;h.&quot;

I use the Why symbol because I pronounce it.  Those who don&#39;t pronounce 
it, presumably don&#39;t use the symbol.  It does not cause any difficulty 
in reading in my opinion.

I also make the distinction between Awe-Ah-Ox.  When I hear someone 
pronounce &quot;nautical&quot; as if it were spelled &quot;notical&quot; it seems very 
peculiar to me.  How do you pronounce the word &quot;Awe&quot;?  Does it just 
sound like the vowel in &quot;on&quot;?

Good luck in your QS studies.  I hope the site is useful to you and that 
you make good progress.  Remember, practice makes perfect.

Paige Gabhart


